Why does US have a street gang problem ? I am not sure if I am obvious here, but I think it is the environment, the ghettos. I hope that I am not offending anybody here again, but I think the chances for a kid growing up in the ghettos is significantly less than a kid in another neighbourhood. Like Janus said, a sense of belonging is a big motivation for kids to join gangs.<br>
<br>
The solution is to get rid of ghettos, but how ? It's very hard, in Holland we're actually trying to figure out the answer to that problem also (although we have no gang problem). The key is to spread the demographics over the city, of course, that is very hard to put to practice.<br>
<br>
I think the first step is that ghettos should be acknowledged as an American problem, instead of a racial problem. You don't hear presidents talking about this a lot(of course, maybe it's just because European media don't find it interesting). I know of an example in France, where they just pumped money in a ghetto to make the area more pleasant. More trees, more playgrounds, more police to keep crime of the streets, etc, etc. Poor people still live there, but crime had gone down a lot. Downside is that it would cost a huge amount of money.<br>
<br>
The accessibility of guns contributes a lot to the problem too, in my opinion. I doubt as many gang-related deaths would occur if they didn't have as many guns.<br>
